<div id="comment_status_65472569" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_65472569" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65472569" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65472569" name="comment_link_65472569" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23726903&amp;cid=65472569" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65472569)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65472569" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65472569); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~DamnOregonian">DamnOregonian</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~DamnOregonian">( 963763 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65472569"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65472569"><p><div class="quote"><p>I wonder, had Anthropic bought a copy of all of those books, e-book or physical, and then done the same, would that have been considered fair use?</p></div><p>Yes.<br>
<br>
What's at question here is how the data is used to train the model. Regardless of how it's acquired, the training is fair use, because it's highly transformative.<br>
There are other considerations on top of that- but acquisition isn't one of them.<br>
<br>
If you borrow a book from a friend, feed it into a hashing algorithm, you doing that, while technically in violation of copyright, is fair use.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65472569">

</div>
